ters, O’Connor shows, marketed spectacular visions of past worlds, piquing the public imagination with glimpses of man-eating mammoths, talking dinosaurs, and sea-dragons spawned by Satan himself. These authors—including men of science, women, clergymen, biblical literalists, hack writers, blackmailers, and prophets—borrowed freely from the Bible, modern poetry, and the urban entertainment industry, creating new forms of literature in order to transport their readers into a vanished and alien past. In exploring the use of poetry and spectacle in the promotion of popular science, O’Connor proves that geology’s success owed much to the literary techniques of its authors. An innovative blend of the history of science, literary criticism, book history, and visual culture, The Earth on Show rethinks the relationship between science and literature in the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGeology in literature. 0aGeologyxSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aGeologyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and historyzGreat Britain. 0aLiterature and sciencezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy19th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  afossils, popular science, television, geology, victorian, britain, england, geohistory, religion, past worlds, satan, sea dragons, dinosaurs, mammoths, bible, poetry, prophets, blackmail, sensation, biblical literalists, clergymen, women, gender, entertainment, literature, urban, spectacle, william buckland, lyell, hugh miller, deep time, diorama, john martin, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022661668140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226616704423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt